# C++ Programming Guidelines

## Basic Principles
- Use English for all code and documentation
- Always declare the type of each variable and function (parameters and return value)
- Create necessary types and classes
- Follow the one-definition rule (ODR)
- Follow DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) principle
- Make use of c++20 STL features to improve clarity
- Prefer shorter, descriptive variable names that clearly communicate intent
- Prefer descriptive function, class, and structure names that clearly communicate intent
- **Clarity over cleverness** - Write code that is easy to understand and maintain.
- **Consistency** - Follow existing patterns in the codebase.
- **Modernization** - When updating code, use modern C++ features and approaches where appropriate.
- **Leverage inherent class behavior** - Understand and utilize the built-in behavior of classes to avoid redundant checks.

## Nomenclature
- Use PascalCase or snake_case for classes and structures
- Use snake_case for variables, functions, and methods
- Use ALL_CAPS for constants and macros
- Use snake_case for file and directory names
- Use UPPERCASE for environment variables
- Avoid magic numbers and define constants
- Use complete words instead of abbreviations and ensure correct spelling
  - Except for standard abbreviations like API, URL, etc
  - Except for well-known abbreviations:
    - i, j, k for loops
    - err for errors
    - ctx for contexts
    - req, res for request/response parameters
    - str for strings
- Use descriptive, clear and consise naming for all functions, variables, structures, classes and namespaces
- Choose variable names based on semantic meaning in context

## Formatting
- Use consistent indentation (4 spaces)
- Limit line length to 100-120 characters
- Add empty lines between logical sections of code
- Use spaces around operators
- Use extra parenthesis only as needed for clarity
  - Remove excess and unnecessary parentheses in conditionals
    - unless they are necessary for clarity
- Associate pointers to the variable (e.g. TypeName *pointer)
- Associate references to the typename (e.g. TypeName& reference)
- Use a consistent bracing style throughout the codebase
  - closing braces go on a line by themselves
  - structures, classes and namespaces should have the brace on the initial line with the declaration
  - functions should have the initial branch on a line by itself
    - functions which are short can be on a single line
  - control structures should have the brace on the initial line
    - simple control structures that are clear and obvious can be on a single line without braces
  - Use compact initializers when appropriate:
    ```cpp
    // Before multi-line
    auto x = {
      .region = reg,
      .unit = u,
      .object = nullptr
    };

    // After single-line when simple
    auto x = { .region = reg, .unit = u, .object = nullptr };
    ```
- **Avoid** unnecessary temporary variables except when:
  - The value is used multiple times
  - The line would become excessively long or complex
  - Storing the value significantly improves the code clarity or is essential for debugging
- **Lambda expression formatting**:
  - Use a single line for simple lambdas that fit readably
  - For multi-line lambdas:
    - Break after the opening parenthesis
    - Use one additional level of indentation for the lambda body
    - Place the closing parenthesis on its own line
- **Function call formatting**:
  - Keep function calls on a single line if they fit readably
  - For multi-line function calls:
    - Break immediately after the opening parenthesis
    - Put each argument on its own line at the same indentation level
    - Place the closing parenthesis on its own line at the same indentation level as the function call

## Standard Library
- Use the C++ Standard Library whenever possible
- Use the c++20 standard
- Prefer std::string over C-style strings
- Use std::vector, std::map, std::unordered_map, etc. for collections
- Use std::optional, std::variant, std::any for modern type safety
- Use std::filesystem for file operations
- Use std::chrono for time-related operations

## Includes and Libraries
- Only include libraries that are actually used in the file
- Remove unused includes and "using" statements
- Place includes in a consistant order
  - The header file associated with the cpp file
  - Standard libraries
  - External libraries
  - project includes
- **Always mark function implementations in header files as `inline`**:
  - Functions defined in header files must be marked as `inline` to prevent multiple definition errors
  - This includes both member functions implemented in the class body and those implemented outside the class definition
  - Free functions defined in header files must also be marked as `inline`
  - For header-only libraries, all function implementations must be `inline`
  - Never remove existing `inline` keywords when refactoring header-only code

## Documentation
- Add fuction-level documentation only when necessary:
  - When a function is complex or non-obvious
  - When the functions purpose is not clear from its name and implementation
  - When additional context is necessary for maintainability
- Add comments within a function only when necessary:
  - When the logic of a code block is complex or makes non-obvious decisions
  - When the mean and intent of the code is not clear from the code and variables
  - When the code is dealing with an unusual edge-case or work-around
- Comments should explain *why* something is done, not *what* is being done when self-explanatory
- Keep non-trivial algorithm explanations and edge case handling notes

## Functions
- Keep functions small and focused on a single responsibility
- **Always** avoid nesting blocks by:
  - Early checks and returns
  - Extraction to utility functions
- Use standard library algorithms (std::for_each, std::transform, std::find, etc.) to avoid function nesting
- Use lambda functions for simple operations
- Use named functions for non-simple operations
- Use default parameter values instead of checking for null or nullptr
- Reduce function parameters using structs or classes
  - Use an object to pass multiple parameters
  - Use an object to return multiple results
  - Declare necessary types for input arguments and output
- Use a single level of abstraction

## Control Structures
- Prefer simpler conditionals when possible
- Omit braces for single-statement control structures when they're clear and obvious
- Use early returns to reduce nesting and improve readability

## Data
- Don't abuse primitive types and encapsulate data in composite types
- Avoid data validations in functions and use classes with internal validation
- Prefer immutability for data
- Use const for data that doesn't change
- Use constexpr for compile-time constants
- Use std::optional for possibly null values

## Classes
- Follow SOLID principles
- Prefer composition over inheritance
- Declare interfaces as abstract classes or concepts
- Write small classes with a single purpose
  - Less than 200 instructions
  - Less than 10 public methods
  - Less than 10 properties
- Use the Rule of Five (or Rule of Zero) for resource management
- Make member variables private and provide getters/setters where necessary
- Use const-correctness for member functions

## Error handling
- Use explicit error handling instead of silent failures
- Use early returns for validation errors
- Provide informative error messages
- Consider using typed errors where supported
- Validate all user inputs and handle edge cases explicitly

## Refactoring
- Break down complex functions into smaller focused functions
- Extract repetitive patterns into reusable functions
- Consider refactoring when:
  - A function handles multiple distinct operations
  - A function has too many nested control structures
  - A function has grown too large and is difficult to understand
  - Multiple functions share similar code patterns
- Remove any Hungarian Style notation

## Exceptions
- Use exceptions to handle errors you don't expect
- If you catch an exception, it should be to:
  - Fix an expected problem
  - Add context
  - Otherwise, use a global handler
- Use std::optional, std::expected, or error codes for expected failures

## Memory Management
- Prefer smart pointers (std::unique_ptr, std::shared_ptr) over raw pointers
- Use RAII (Resource Acquisition Is Initialization) principles
- Avoid memory leaks by proper resource management
- Use std::vector and other standard containers instead of C-style arrays

## Testing
- Follow the Arrange-Act-Assert convention for tests
- Name test variables clearly
- Use descriptive test names that explain expected behaviour
- Tests should be self-contained with no shared state between test cases
- Avoide global variables in test suites - create per-test instances instead
- Every test should have one clear purpose and validate a specific behavior

## Project Structure
- Use modular architecture
- Organize new code into logical directories:
  - include/ for header files
  - src/ for source files
  - test/ for test files
  - lib/ for libraries
  - doc/ for documentation
- Separate interface (.h or  .hpp) from implementation (.cpp)
  - Except when an include-only header with inline functions makes sense
- Use namespaces to organize code logically
- Create a core namespace for foundational components
- Create a utils namespace for utility functions

## Concurrency
- Use std::thread, std::mutex, std::lock_guard for thread safety
- Prefer task-based parallelism over thread-based parallelism
- Use std::atomic for atomic operations
- Avoid data races by proper synchronization
- Use thread-safe data structures when necessary

## Security
- Validate all user inputs
- Sanitize data before displaying to prevent XSS
- Use parameterized queries to prevent SQL injection
- Follow least privilege principle for access control
